function buildThirtySeventhArticle(siteKey) {
  return {
    id: `${siteKey}-loneliness-being-misunderstood-conventional-pedagogies`,
    title:
      'The Loneliness of Being Misunderstood: RealLives in a World of Conventional Pedagogies',
    excerpt:
      'A reflection on how RealLives challenges conventional education by centering empathy, transformation, and global human connection.',
    category: 'Teaching Strategy',
    tags: ['Empathy', 'Pedagogy', 'Global Citizenship'],
    author: 'Parag Mankeekar',
    authorRole:
      "Co-Founder @ RealLives Foundation | RealLives Simulation, Edupreneur, 'Games for Good & Changemaking' advocator",
    authorAvatar:
      'https://d2jn82ki4w4ftn.cloudfront.net/reallives-website/common-newsletter-page/ceo-image.jpg',
    publishedOn: 'January 28, 2025',
    readTime: '10 min read',
    readMinutes: 10,
    imagePath:
      'https://d2jn82ki4w4ftn.cloudfront.net/reallives-website/common-newsletter-page/article-37-bg.png',
    content: [
      '“The most terrible loneliness is not the kind that comes from being alone, but the kind that comes from being misunderstood. It is the loneliness of standing in a crowded room, surrounded by people who do not see you, who do not hear you, who do not know the true essence of who you are. And in that loneliness, you feel as though you are fading, disappearing into the background, until you are nothing more than a ghost, a shadow of your former self.”',
      '— George Orwell, 1984',
      'This poignant observation captures the existential challenge faced by many visionary ideas in education - ideas that push the boundaries of what is possible, yet often find themselves struggling for recognition in a world entrenched in convention. At RealLives Simulation, we experience this loneliness in a deeply personal way.',
      'RealLives is not a conventional educational tool. It is not designed to simply teach facts, improve test scores, or check boxes on a curriculum. It is a simulation that seeks to transform the way people see the world and each other. It invites users to step into the lives of individuals from vastly different cultural, economic, and social realities. It fosters empathy, global citizenship, and a profound understanding of what it means to live as someone else. But in an education ecosystem that often prioritizes predictability, standardization, and measurable outcomes, such a mission can feel misunderstood, even invisible.',
      'This is the story of how RealLives navigates the loneliness of being different - standing in the crowded room of conventional education, often unseen but steadfast in its commitment to change the way we learn and connect.',
      'The Crowded Room of Conventional Education',
      'Education, as it stands today, is often a crowded room filled with established norms, deeply rooted traditions, and familiar frameworks. Standardized tests, rigid curricula, and performance metrics dominate the space. In this room, anything that deviates from the norm is often met with skepticism, hesitation, or outright dismissal.',
      'RealLives enters this space not with textbooks or lesson plans but with questions:',
      'What if students could learn empathy the way they learn math or science?',
      "What if education didn't just prepare students for exams but for life in a globally interconnected world?",
      "What if the goal wasn't just to impart knowledge but to inspire a shift in perspective?",
      'These are not easy questions, nor are they ones that fit neatly into traditional paradigms. RealLives challenges the status quo by offering a deeply immersive experience where students do not just learn about the world - they live it. They make choices, face consequences, and grapple with the complexities of life across cultures, economic conditions, and societal norms.',
      'But in the crowded room of conventional education, such questions often go unanswered. Decision-makers seek alignment with test scores, while educators grapple with tight schedules and rigid syllabi. In this room, RealLives often stands as a quiet voice, offering an alternative vision that few are ready to embrace.',
      'The Loneliness of Being Misunderstood',
      'The loneliness of RealLives does not stem from isolation. On the contrary, we are surrounded by passionate educators, policymakers, and innovators. But often, we find ourselves speaking a language that feels foreign to many.',
      'In the current system, education is largely transactional. It focuses on delivering content, meeting standards, and achieving quantifiable results. But RealLives is transformational. It aims to touch the hearts and minds of learners, nurturing empathy, compassion, and a sense of global responsibility.',
      'This misalignment creates a disconnect. Imagine being in a room where everyone is focused on the "how" of education - how to deliver lessons, how to assess progress, how to meet benchmarks - while RealLives is focused on the "why." Why do we educate? Why should we care about lives beyond our borders? Why does it matter that students understand the interconnectedness of humanity?',
      'The loneliness comes from the sense of being unheard, of having a vision that is difficult to quantify or fit into conventional frameworks. It is the loneliness of standing in a room where people see only the surface of what you offer and miss the depth of what you truly represent.',
      'Challenging the Status Quo',
      'RealLives exists to challenge this very status quo. It dares to ask whether the ultimate purpose of education is more than just preparing students for careers or meeting academic standards. It proposes that education should also prepare students to be compassionate, ethical, and globally minded citizens.',
      'In doing so, RealLives disrupts traditional pedagogies in several ways:',
      '1. Learning Through Empathy',
      'Conventional education often separates knowledge from lived experience. Students learn about poverty, inequality, and cultural differences from a distance through statistics, case studies, or historical narratives. RealLives, however, brings these realities to life by placing learners directly in the shoes of individuals around the world.',
      'This experiential approach often feels alien in systems that prioritize abstract knowledge over emotional connection. Yet, it is precisely this emotional engagement that makes RealLives transformative.',
      '2. Shifting the Focus from Measurable Outcomes',
      'In an era where educational success is often measured by grades and test scores, RealLives measures success differently. Its impact lies in the stories users share: stories of changed perspectives, newfound empathy, and a deeper understanding of global issues.',
      'But these outcomes are not easily captured in metrics or standardized tests. And so, in a system that values what can be measured, RealLives risks being overlooked.',
      '3. Prioritizing Humanity Over Homogeneity',
      'Traditional education systems often aim to produce uniform outcomes - a common body of knowledge and a shared set of skills. RealLives, however, celebrates diversity. It recognizes that no two learners will have the same experience, because no two lives are the same.',
      'This emphasis on individuality and human complexity challenges the one-size-fits-all approach of conventional education. It invites discomfort, questions, and, sometimes, resistance.',
      'Finding Connection Amid Loneliness',
      'Yet, even in this loneliness, RealLives has found allies - educators, researchers, and changemakers who see its potential and share its vision. These individuals and institutions recognize that the world is changing and that education must change with it.',
      'In K12 classrooms, teachers use RealLives to foster social-emotional learning and global citizenship. They see how the simulation helps students step beyond stereotypes and develop empathy for others.',
      'In higher education, RealLives is used in entrepreneurship and social innovation workshops to help students understand the complexities of real-world challenges. It inspires future changemakers to create solutions grounded in empathy and respect for human dignity.',
      'At global conferences, RealLives has been celebrated as a tool that bridges gaps between cultures, breaks down barriers, and promotes understanding in an increasingly divided world.',
      'Each of these connections is a reminder that the loneliness of being misunderstood is not permanent. With persistence, vision, and a commitment to authenticity, RealLives continues to find those who see its true essence and are willing to stand beside it.',
      'The Power of Being Different',
      'While the loneliness of RealLives can feel heavy at times, it is also a source of strength. Standing apart from the crowd allows us to see the flaws in conventional systems and imagine bold alternatives. It gives us the courage to ask difficult questions, push boundaries, and remain true to our mission, even when it is not fully understood.',
      'The very things that make RealLives different - its focus on empathy, its experiential approach, its resistance to standardization - are also the things that make it powerful. They are what allow it to touch hearts, change lives, and inspire a new vision for education.',
      'An Invitation to Walk In Our Shoes',
      'To educators, policymakers, and changemakers who feel the same loneliness we do: you are not alone. The work of transforming education is not easy, but it is necessary. Together, we can create a world where education is not just about learning but about understanding the real world and connecting with it. Not just about succeeding but about connecting with humanity.',
      'To those who see RealLives for what it truly is: thank you. Your support and belief fuel our journey.',
      'And to those who may not yet understand us: we invite you to join us, to step into the lives of others, to experience the world through new eyes. For it is only by seeing, hearing, and knowing each other that we can truly create a future worth striving for.',
    ],
  };
}

