      'Introduction: A New Kind of Teaching for a New Kind of World',
      'What if the role of a teacher was no longer to deliver the world to students - but to help them discover it for themselves, equipped with curiosity, empathy, and agency? This is the future the OECD Teaching Compass for 2030 envisions - a future where teachers are empowered, supported, and trusted to guide learners through complexity and change.',
      'Turning this vision into everyday classroom reality demands more than a framework. It requires pedagogical partners - tools and practices that embody the very values we hope to instill. This is where RealLives, a data-driven life simulation platform, stands out. Rather than presenting knowledge as a finished product, RealLives immerses students in the lived experiences of others across the globe, turning learning into a journey of empathy, inquiry, and moral engagement.',
      'And in doing so, RealLives becomes not just a learning resource, but a professional ally for educators. It supports the Teaching Compass pillars - teacher agency, well-being, and future-ready competencies - through a pedagogy that is student-driven, emotionally resonant, and globally aware.',
      '1. From Delivering Content to Facilitating Curiosity: Real Teacher Agency',
      'The OECD Teaching Compass defines agency as more than autonomy - it is the ability to act with purpose, adapt to context, and shape learning in meaningful ways.',
      'RealLives enables true teacher agency by offering an open platform, not a prescriptive curriculum. Educators can align the simulation with nearly any subject - from literature to economics, geography to ethics. They decide which global challenges to explore, which narratives to deepen, and how to structure student reflection and dialogue.',
      'This flexibility empowers teachers to become co-creators of learning, not passive implementers. But more importantly, by shifting the cognitive and emotional momentum of learning to students, RealLives frees teachers from performative pressures. They guide instead of deliver. They respond instead of orchestrate. In short, they teach with agency, not anxiety.',
      '2. Well-being through Student-Driven Learning',
      'Teacher well-being is not just about reduced workload - it is about meaningful work, professional trust, and sustainable emotional energy. The OECD Teaching Compass rightly positions well-being as foundational, not incidental.',
      'Here, RealLives offers a unique contribution: it transforms classrooms from teacher-centered instruction to student-driven exploration. When students simulate lives in contexts like Rwanda, Bolivia, or Bangladesh, they begin to ask powerful, self-directed questions - Why did my character leave school at 12? Why did their child die of a preventable illness? These are not imposed prompts. They are natural consequences of curiosity.',
      'This dynamic lightens the cognitive load on teachers. They no longer have to invent engaging hooks or force connections across abstract themes. RealLives organically introduces complex, interdisciplinary narratives - grounded in global data and real-world systems.',
      'Moreover, the emotional depth of the simulation allows teachers to connect meaningfully without having to create emotional resonance from scratch. As one teacher remarked, "RealLives gave me everything I needed to bring the world into the room - without exhausting myself trying to be the world."',
      'In this way, RealLives supports well-being not by removing the emotional labor of teaching - but by making that labor authentic, sustainable, and shared.',
      '3. Competency as Capability: Teaching for Life, Not Just for School',
      'The OECD Teaching Compass emphasizes the importance of transformative competencies: the ability to create value, reconcile tensions, and take responsibility. RealLives is uniquely positioned to make these competencies felt, not just understood.',
      'Every student who uses RealLives must make real-life decisions in uncertain conditions. Should I marry for stability or pursue education? Should I migrate or stay? Should I invest in my child\'s future or respond to a current crisis?',
      'These dilemmas develop critical thinking, ethical reasoning, and systemic awareness. Students do not just learn about global inequality - they experience it. They do not debate poverty abstractly - they watch it unfold through the simulated lifespan of a person who could be their peer, their opposite, or their mirror.',
      'This kind of learning develops capabilities, not just skills. It builds the mindset, empathy, and responsibility the Teaching Compass envisions - and it gives teachers the opportunity to facilitate transformation, not just instruction.',
      '4. A World of Stories, A Community of Practice: The RealLives Teacher Project',
      'To support collaborative professionalism, the OECD emphasizes the need for teacher networks and shared innovation. RealLives responds by launching the RealLives Teacher Project - a global initiative where educators share how they\'ve used the simulation to break disciplinary boundaries and deepen global learning.',
      'Already, educators from Finland, India, Korea, and Canada are:',
      'Sharing lesson plans that connect language learning with social justice.',
      'Designing worksheets and prompts to explore the SDGs through narrative.',
      'Merging data analysis and storytelling in new interdisciplinary ways.',
      'Hosting reflections where students discuss how they would redesign societies or advocate for change.',
      'This is not a marketplace of ideas. It is a global conversation about what teaching can become. Through the Teacher Project, RealLives becomes a medium for professional identity, peer learning, and co-creation - just as the Teaching Compass envisions.',
      '5. Case Study: Mathematics Meets Empathy at Gunseo Global School, South Korea',
      'An inspiring example comes from Kyungsuk Kim, a mathematics teacher at Gunseo Global School in South Korea, who embedded RealLives in her course "Understanding the World with Big Data."',
